name of the authors

In informing the debate on the AIDS pandemic in South Africa, there are many lessons to be learnt from the experience of other developing countries, described below.

The essay considers the question posed by Michael Coyle (1995:230) on African agency in the contemporary period, namely : how much of the modern reality is an expression of indigenous vision, assertion, and leadership and how much does it reflect that which is imposed, controlled and determined by western forces? The question is approached through a brief discussion of ''modernity'' as understood in the African context which, paradoxically, takes very little account of the African continent as the deep well-spring of the modern ''wold-system'', as emphasised by Paul Kennedy (1987).
